<template>
  <div>
    <p class="back-link"><router-link :to="{ path: '/projects', query: { to: 'insurance' } }">&larr; Back to projects</router-link></p>
    <h1 data-scroll-reveal>Insurance Product Configuration Engine</h1>

    <article data-scroll-group data-scroll-step="110">
      <p class="lede">
        Here's something you've done a hundred times: <strong>packing for a trip</strong>. The kind of trip decides
        what goes in the bag. Say "beach" and you need swimwear; add "water sports" and a snorkel earns its place;
        say "ski" and it's a completely different bag. You're running a tiny rules engine in your head, turning a few
        answers into the right list.
      </p>
      <p>
        At <strong>HSBC</strong> I built exactly that engine, for a much harder version of the same problem. Below is
        a small, fully playable version. It takes a couple of minutes, and the second half hands you the controls.
      </p>

      <!-- 1 · THE PROBLEM -->
      <h2>First, the real problem</h2>
      <p>
        Picture one banking app that sells many kinds of insurance. Every product needs a
        <strong>different set of screens</strong>: a travel policy asks for trip dates, a car policy asks about your
        vehicle, and some questions only appear once an earlier answer unlocks them. Now multiply that by dozens of
        products across a dozen markets.
      </p>
      <p>
        The rules for "which screen shows when" lived scattered in people's heads. Business knew the requirements,
        designers knew the screens, developers wired it together, and over time the three drifted out of sync.
        There was no single place you could point to and say <em>this</em> is how a product becomes a set of screens.
      </p>

      <!-- 2 · THE IDEA -->
      <h2>The idea: stop mixing three questions</h2>
      <p>I split the mess into three small libraries, each owned by the team that actually knows the answer:</p>
      <div class="lib-cards" data-scroll-group data-scroll-step="120">
        <div class="lib-card">
          <span class="lib-tag">Spec</span>
          <p>What does the business need to know? <em>The questions.</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="lib-card">
          <span class="lib-tag">Components</span>
          <p>What has the team actually built? <em>The building blocks.</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="lib-card">
          <span class="lib-tag">Config</span>
          <p>Small rule tables linking the two: given these answers, use these blocks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        Because they're separate, business can add a question, design can add a block, and neither breaks the other.
        Those <strong>rule tables</strong> are where the magic happens, and they're what you'll drive next.
      </p>

      <!-- 3 · THE PLAYGROUND -->
      <h2>Now you try it</h2>
      <p class="play-intro">
        Same machine, on the friendly example: you're packing for a trip. Answer the questions, watch each little rule
        table pick a winner, then watch the bag fill with exactly the right things.
      </p>

      <div class="playground" data-scroll-pop="true">

        <!-- STEP 1 — answer -->
        <section class="stage">
          <header class="stage-head"><span class="stage-num">1</span> Tell us about the trip</header>
          <div class="qform">
            <label v-for="f in visible" :key="f.sno" class="qrow" :class="{ 'is-sub': f.parent }">
              <span class="qlabel">
                <span v-if="f.parent" class="sub-arrow">↳</span>{{ f.name }}
              </span>
              <select v-model="answers[f.sno]" class="qselect">
                <option v-for="p in f.params" :key="p" :value="p">{{ p }}</option>
              </select>
            </label>
          </div>
          <p class="stage-note" v-if="hasSub">
            Notice the follow-up question appears only when it's relevant. In the real tool that condition is written
            right into the field's name, so the form reshapes itself as you fill it in.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- STEP 2 — rules react, one table per decision -->
        <section class="stage">
          <header class="stage-head"><span class="stage-num">2</span> Each decision gets its own rule table</header>
          <p class="stage-note stage-note--top">
            Every table works the same way: keep the columns whose conditions all match your answers, and the most
            specific one on the right wins. <strong>ALL</strong> is a wildcard that matches anything.
          </p>

          <div v-for="group in ev.groups" :key="group.cfg.id" class="cfg">
            <div class="cfg-head">
              <span class="cfg-name">{{ group.cfg.name }}</span>
              <span class="cfg-blurb">{{ group.cfg.blurb }}</span>
            </div>
            <div class="table-scroll">
              <table class="rules">
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th class="rowhead"></th>
                    <th
                      v-for="(s, j) in group.cfg.scenarios" :key="s.name"
                      class="schead"
                      :class="{ matched: group.results[j].match, winning: group.winning === j }"
                    >{{ s.name }}</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr class="group-row"><td :colspan="group.cfg.scenarios.length + 1">Your answers (inputs)</td></tr>
                  <tr v-for="sno in group.cfg.inputs" :key="sno" :class="{ dim: !ev.visible.has(sno) }">
                    <td class="rowhead">{{ fname(sno) }}</td>
                    <td
                      v-for="(s, j) in group.cfg.scenarios" :key="s.name"
                      class="cell spec-cell"
                      :class="{ colmatch: group.results[j].match, winning: group.winning === j, bad: !group.results[j].cell[sno].ok }"
                    >{{ group.results[j].cell[sno].req }}</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr class="group-row"><td :colspan="group.cfg.scenarios.length + 1">What to pack (outputs)</td></tr>
                  <tr v-for="id in group.cfg.items" :key="id">
                    <td class="rowhead">{{ iname(id) }}</td>
                    <td
                      v-for="(s, j) in group.cfg.scenarios" :key="s.name"
                      class="cell comp-cell"
                      :class="[ s.out[id] === 'Y' ? 'yes' : 'no', { colmatch: group.results[j].match, winning: group.winning === j } ]"
                    >{{ s.out[id] }}</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p class="cfg-note">
              <template v-if="matchCount(group) > 1">
                Your answers match {{ matchCount(group) }} columns; the most specific,
                <strong>“{{ winnerName(group) }}”</strong>, wins.
              </template>
              <template v-else>
                Your answers land on <strong>“{{ winnerName(group) }}”</strong>.
              </template>
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- STEP 3 — the bag packs itself -->
        <section class="stage">
          <header class="stage-head"><span class="stage-num">3</span> The bag packs itself</header>
          <div class="phone-wrap">
            <div class="phone">
              <div class="phone-notch"></div>
              <div class="phone-screen">
                <div class="app-bar">
                  <span>Packing list</span>
                  <span class="app-count">{{ ev.shown.length }}</span>
                </div>
                <div class="app-body">
                  <div v-for="c in ev.shown" :key="c.id" class="app-card">
                    <span class="app-check" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                    <span class="app-card-text">
                      <span class="app-card-title">{{ c.name }}</span>
                      <span class="app-card-hint">{{ c.hint }}</span>
                    </span>
                  </div>
                  <div v-if="!ev.shown.length" class="app-empty">
                    Just the essentials for this trip.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="phone-side">
              <p class="phone-caption">
                Same answers in, the same list out, every time. Each table contributes its part, and together they
                build the bag. Nobody has to remember the rules, because the tables do.
              </p>
              <div v-for="group in ev.groups" :key="group.cfg.id" class="legend-group">
                <span class="legend-title">{{ group.cfg.name }}</span>
                <ul class="comp-legend">
                  <li v-for="id in group.cfg.items" :key="id" :class="ev.out[id] === 'Y' ? 'on' : 'off'">
                    <span class="dot"></span>{{ iname(id) }}
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>

      <!-- 4 · WHAT IT REALLY WAS -->
      <h2>What this really was</h2>
      <p>
        The real version ran in Excel, driven by a roughly 32&nbsp;KB VBA engine. It had a small custom language for those
        conditional follow-up questions, a stack of decision tables with wildcards and right-side overrides (exactly what
        you just used), and live form behaviour so non-coders could fill it in without breaking anything. It went through
        four versions and shipped with a built-in tutorial so the next person could take it over.
      </p>
      <p>
        The packing example here stands in for confidential product data, but the machinery is the real thing: a way to
        turn scattered, tribal business logic into one structure that a team, and a computer, can both read.
      </p>
      <p class="back-link"><router-link :to="{ path: '/projects', query: { to: 'insurance' } }">← Back to projects</router-link></p>
    </article>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import scrollRevealMixin from '../mixins/scrollRevealMixin';
import { fields, components, configurators, visibleFields, evaluate, defaultAnswers, fieldBySno, componentById } from '../data/playbookDemo';

export default {
  name: 'PlaybookTab',
  mixins: [scrollRevealMixin],
  data() {
    return {
      fields,
      components,
      configurators,
      answers: defaultAnswers(),
    };
  },
  computed: {
    visible() { return visibleFields(this.answers); },
    hasSub() { return this.visible.some(f => f.parent); },
    ev() { return evaluate(this.answers); },
  },
  methods: {
    fname(sno) { const f = fieldBySno(sno); return f ? f.name : sno; },
    iname(id) { const c = componentById(id); return c ? c.name : id; },
    matchCount(group) { return group.results.filter(r => r.match).length; },
    winnerName(group) { return group.winning >= 0 ? group.cfg.scenarios[group.winning].name : '—'; },
  },
};
</script>

